Exercises about lapply and sapply

For the next 5ish minutes, lets talk through some coding questions

Question 1: How would you write the following for loop as an sapply?

n_vec <- c(1,5,10,100,1000)
set.seed(0)
mean_vec <- rep(NA, length = length(n_vec))
for(i in 1:length(n_vec)){
  dat <- rnorm(n_vec[i])
  mean_vec[i] <- mean(dat)
}

Answer:

round(mean_vec,2)
## [1]  1.26  0.23 -0.10 -0.01 -0.04
set.seed(0)
mean_vec2 <- sapply(n_vec, function(n){
  dat <- rnorm(n)
  return(mean(dat))
})
round(mean_vec2,2)
## [1]  1.26  0.23 -0.10 -0.01 -0.04

Question 2: How would you write the following lapply as a for loop?

make_matrix <- function(n){
  return(matrix(0, nrow = n, ncol = n))
}
result <- lapply(1:5, make_matrix)

Answer:

Question 3 (Last question): What happens with these lines of code?

make_fixed_vector <- function(n){
  return(rep(n, nrow = 5))
}
result <- sapply(1:5, make_fixed_vector)

make_adaptive_vector <- function(n){
  return(rep(0, length = n))
}
result2 <- sapply(1:5, make_adaptive_vector)

Answer:

result
## [1] 1 2 3 4 5
result2
## [[1]]
## [1] 0
## 
## [[2]]
## [1] 0 0
## 
## [[3]]
## [1] 0 0 0
## 
## [[4]]
## [1] 0 0 0 0
## 
## [[5]]
## [1] 0 0 0 0 0
  • Whenever sapply realizes your results are all the same length, it outputs your results as a matrix (where each column corresponds to a different function call).
  • When its all different lengths, sapply returns a list instead (and essentially comes an lapply).

Tidyverse

Source: https://r4ds.had.co.nz/introduction.html

tibbles

Data frames are great! Except for

  • printing them
  • working with both characters and factors
  • manipulating multiple columns

tibbles are the data frame alternative of the tidyverse

tibbles

A tibble, or tbl_df, is a modern reimagining of the data.frame, keeping what time has proven to be effective, and throwing out what is not. Tibbles are data.frames that are lazy and surly: they do less (i.e.they dont change variable names or types, and dont do partial matching) and complain more (e.g.when a variable does not exist). This forces you to confront problems earlier, typically leading to cleaner, more expressive code. Tibbles also have an enhanced print method() which makes them easier to use with large datasets containing complex objects.

  • Hadley Wickham, Chief Scientist at RStudio

How do we read code?

Translate the following code into words:

length(unique(covid_testing$clinic_name))
## [1] 88

Intuitive coding

covid_testing %>% pull(clinic_name) %>% unique %>% length
## [1] 88

Data analysis with tidyverse

Lets look at how we might answer the following data analysis questions:

  • Which patient was the oldest?
  • How many days into the pandemic did positive cases appear?
  • What was the precentage of positives among age?

Using filter()

Which patient(s) was the oldest?

covid_testing %>%
  filter(age == max(age))

Using summarize()

What was the precentage of positives among males above the age of 20?

covid_testing %>%

Using summarize()

Even better

Using group_by()

What was the precentage of positives among each clinic?

positive_rate_tib <- covid_testing %>%
  group_by(age) %>%
  summarise(positive_rate = length(

            n=n())

group_by() allows you to perform any operation by group

Writing beautiful code

The alternative:

unique_ages <- sort(unique(covid_testing$age))
positive_rate <- sapply(unique_ages, function(age){
  idx <- which(covid_testing$age == age)
  n <- length(idx)
  positive_n <- length(which(covid_testing$result[idx] == "positive"))
  positive_n/n
})

dplyr

dplyr is a grammar of data manipulation, providing a consistent set of verbs that help you solve the most common data manipulation challenges:

  • filter() picks cases based on their values.
  • summarise() reduces multiple values down to a single summary.
  • mutate() adds new variables that are functions of existing variables
  • select() picks variables based on their names.
  • arrange() changes the ordering of the rows

These all combine naturally with group_by() which allows you to perform any operation by group.

The pipe

%>% is included in every tidyverse package

  • x %>% f is equivalent to f(x)
  • x %>% f() is equivalent to f(x)
  • x %>% f(y) is equivalent to f(x, y)
  • x %>% f(y, .) is equivalent to f(y, x)

Advanced piping

There are actually multiple different types of pipes (not just %>%)

You need to load magrittr to use the following:

  • covid_testing %$% name is covid_testing[, "name"] as a vector
  • x %<>% f is equivalent to x <- f(x)

Watch out!

covid_testing 
  %>% filter(result == "positive") %>% 
  pull(pan_day)
## Error: <text>:2:3: unexpected SPECIAL
## 1: covid_testing 
## 2:   %>%
##      ^

Graphics

Graphical communication in practice

Graphical communication is critical for both exploring and explaining data.

There are lots of different ways to make graphics in R.

Today, were going to talk about ggplot: a toolkit for creating beautiful, data-rich statistical graphics in R!

ggplot

  • ggplot is a function available in the ggplot2 package.
  • Graphics are built in layers: a plot is initialised, then data is then drawn, then annotations are added.
  • Annotations include
    • scales
    • labels
    • legends
    • coordinate systems

Whats in a name? Grammar of Graphics - Leland Wilkinson

All plots can be broken down into core components

  1. data
  2. geometries: type of geometric objects to represent data, e.g., points, lines
  3. aesthetics: visual characteristics of geometric objects to represent data, e.g., position, size
  4. scales: how each aesthetics is converted into values on the graph, e.g., color scales
  5. stats: statistical transformations to summarize data, e.g., counts, means, regression lines
  6. facets: split data and view as multiple graphs
  7. coordinate system: 2D space the data are projected onto, e.g., Cartesian coordinates

Whats in a name? Grammar of Graphics - Leland Wilkinson

All plots can be broken down into core components

  1. data
  2. geometries: type of geometric objects to represent data, e.g., points, lines
  3. aesthetics: visual characteristics of geometric objects to represent data, e.g., position, size
  4. scales: how each aesthetics is converted into values on the graph, e.g., color scales
  5. stats: statistical transformations to summarize data, e.g., counts, means, regression lines
  6. facets: split data and view as multiple graphs
  7. coordinate system: 2D space the data are projected onto, e.g., Cartesian coordinates

Hadley Wickham expanded upon this with ggplot2

  1. data
  2. geom
  3. aes: mappings of columns to geometric objects
  4. scale: one scale for each aes variable
  5. stat:
  6. facet:
  7. coord:
  8. labs: labels/guides for each variable and othe parts of the plot, e.g., title, subtitle, caption
  9. theme: customization of plot layout

Start with the data

Access ggplot2 from the tidyverse:

library(tidyverse)
ggplot(data = fev)

Or equivalently using %>%:

fev %>% ggplot()

Nothing is displayed

Add geometric object with columns mapped to aesthetics

  • Use the + operator in ggplot to add layers
  • Map age to x-axis and fev to the y-axis
fev %>%
ggplot(aes(x = age, y = fev)) + 
geom_point()
  • NOTE we are implicitly saying
fev %>% 
 ggplot(mapping = aes(x = age, 
 y = fev)) + 
 geom_point()

And now we have a scatterplot!

Customise features about the layer

  • Plot elements that use data must be wrapped in a aes() call
ggplot(fev, aes(x = age, y = fev)) + 
geom_point(aes(col = smoke))

We now color the points by smoking!

Modifying the non-plotting elements

  • Adjust global aesthetics outside of aes():
ggplot(fev, aes(x = age, y = fev)) + 
 geom_point(aes(col = smoke)) +
 # add labels
 labs(x = 'Age (years)',
 y = 'Forced Exhalation\nVol. (L/s)',
 title = 'Scatterplot') +
 # change axis
 xlim(0, 20) + ylim(0, 7)

Formatting the plot

Adjusting the aesthetics

  • You can customize aesthetics that involve data!

    • Adding jitter to the points
    • Making the points slightly transparent (via alpha)
    • Changing the color of the points
ggplot(fev, aes(x = age, y = fev, 
 col = smoke)) + 
 geom_jitter(height = 0, width = 0.2, 
 alpha = 0.5) +
 scale_color_manual(values=c("darkblue", 
 "orange")) +
 # add labels
 labs(x = 'Age (years)',
 y = 'Forced Exhalation\nVol. (L/s)',
 title = 'Scatterplot') +
 # change axis
 xlim(0, 20) + ylim(0, 7)

Other types of ggplots

Of course, scatterplots are not the only type of plots!

ggplot(fev, aes(x = fev)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.5)

Other types of ggplots

We can have categorical variables on the x-axis

fev %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = smoke, y = fev)) + theme_bw() +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) + 
  geom_jitter(width = 0.2, height = 0, cex = 0.4) +
  xlab("Smoking status") + ylab("FEV (litres per second)")

Other types of ggplots

or on the y-axis!

fev %>%
  ggplot(aes(y = smoke, x = fev)) + theme_bw() +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) + 
  geom_jitter(width = 0.2, height = 0, cex = 0.4) +
  xlab("Smoking status") + ylab("FEV (litres per second)")

Small multiples: faceting

gapminder %>% 
  filter(country %in% c("Brazil", "China", "India", "United States")) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = lifeExp)) + geom_line() + 
  facet_wrap(~country, nrow=2)

Final tips

  • Align plots with similar axes
    • How do you draw the readers eye towards the point you want to make?
  • Use figures where appropriate
    • Would a table suffice?
  • Critique your own figures
    • Especially before public talks
  • Avoid pie charts
    • Not a good use of space!
